  "prompt": "Why can't India get more medals in Olympics?",
  "response": "India's performance in the Olympics has improved over the years, but several factors have historically contributed to the challenges the country faces in securing more medals:\n\n1. **Funding and Resources**: Compared to countries with strong Olympic traditions, India has historically allocated less funding for sports development. While recent years have seen increased investment, many athletes still struggle with access to quality training facilities, coaching, and equipment.\n\n2. **Sports Infrastructure**: The infrastructure for many sports in India is lacking. Training facilities, playing fields, and sports complexes are often not up to international standards, which can hinder athlete development and performance.\n\n3. **Limited Sports Culture**: Although cricket is immensely popular, other sports often do not receive the same level of public interest or support. This can result in fewer sponsorship opportunities and less media coverage for athletes in non-cricketing sports.\n\n4. **Focus on a Few Sports**: Indian sports have traditionally focused on a handful of disciplines, such as field hockey, wrestling, and badminton. This narrow focus can limit the breadth of talent and investment across other competitive sports where there may be potential for success.\n\n5. **Talent Identification and Development**: Identifying and nurturing talent at a young age is crucial for Olympic success. While this has improved, there is still a need for better systems for scouting and developing athletes in various sports.\n\n6. **Mental Preparation**: The psychological aspect of competing at an elite level is critical. Many Indian athletes have reported struggles with pressure during high-stakes competitions, and mental conditioning is an area that often requires more attention.\n\n7. **Competition**: The level of competition at the Olympics is incredibly high, with many countries investing heavily in sports programs. India competes against nations that have had successful Olympic traditions and experience in producing Olympic medalists.\n\n8. **Government and Policy Support**: Although there are initiatives to support athletes, bureaucratic hurdles and inconsistent policies can sometimes slow down the development and implementation of effective sports programs.\n\nDespite these challenges, it is worth noting that India has made significant strides in recent Olympic Games, achieving a record number of medals in the Tokyo 2020 Olympics (held in 2021) and investing more in sports development at the grassroots and elite levels. Continued focus on these areas may lead to improved performances in future Olympics.",
